V{{Infobox scientist\u000a| name        = Donella Meadows\u000a| image       = File:Cover first edition Limits to growth.jpg\u000a| image_size  = 200px\u000a| birth_date  = {{Birth date |1941|3|13}}\u000a| birth_place = [[Elgin, Illinois]]\u000a| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2001|02|20|1941|3|13}}\u000a| death_place = [[Hanover, New Hampshire]]\u000a| residence   = [[Plainfield, New Hampshire]]\u000a| nationality = [[United States]] \u000a| field       = [[Environmental science]], [[Systems science]]\u000a| workplaces  = [[Dartmouth College|Dartmouth]], [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]\u000a| alma_mater  = [[Harvard University]] Ph.D, 1968<br />[[Carleton College]] B.A., 1963\u000a| doctoral_advisor  = \u000a| doctoral_students =\u000a| known_for    = ''[[The Limits to Growth]]'', [[Twelve leverage points]]\u000a| prizes       = [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellowship]] (1994)<br />Walter C. Paine Science Education Award (1990)\u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Donella H. "Dana" Meadows'''<ref>Diana Wright (Editor) in: Meadows, Donella H. 2008. ''Thinking in systems : a primer''. Chelsea Green Publishing, Vermont, p.XI + 211</ref> (March 13, 1941 \u2013 February 20, 2001) was a pioneering American [[environmental scientist]], teacher, and writer. She is best known as lead author of the influential book ''[[The Limits to Growth]]'' and ''Thinking in Systems: a Primer''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Book Review:  "Thinking in Systems: A Primer" by Donella H. Meadows|url = http://www.dailykos.com/story/2011/11/05/1033372/-Book-Review-Thinking-in-Systems-A-Primer-by-Donella-H-Meadows|website = [[Daily Kos]]|accessdate = 2015-10-25|first = Don|last = Mikulecky|date = 2011-11-04}}</ref>\u000a\u000a== Life ==\u000aBorn in [[Elgin, Illinois]], Meadows was educated in science, receiving a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[chemistry]] from [[Carleton College]] in 1963, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[biophysics]] from [[Harvard University|Harvard]] in 1968.  After a year-long trip from England to Sri Lanka and back, she became a research fellow at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], as a member of a team in the department created by [[Jay Forrester]], the inventor of [[system dynamics]] as well as the principle of magnetic data storage for computers.  She taught at [[Dartmouth College]] for 29 years, beginning in 1972.<ref name = "meadows2008">Meadows, Donella H. 2008. ''Thinking in systems : a primer''. Chelsea Green Publishing, Vermont, p. 213 (About the Author)</ref> She died in 2001 from a bacterial infection.<ref>[http://www.thenation.com/article/171610/limits-growth-book-launched-movement 'The Limits to Growth': A Book That Launched a Movement]</ref>\u000a\u000aMeadows was honored both as a Pew Scholar in Conservation and Environment (1991) and as a [[MacArthur Fellowship|MacArthur Fellow]] (1994).<ref name = "meadows2008" /> She received the Walter C. Paine Science Education Award in 1990. Posthumously, she received the [[John H. Chafee]] Excellence in Environmental Affairs Award for 2001, presented by the [[Conservation Law Foundation]].\u000a\u000aMeadows wrote a weekly column called "The Global Citizen,"<ref name = "meadows2008" /> commenting on world events from a systems point of view. Many of these columns were compiled and published as a book.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=8yE5PzCacXoC&dq=global+citizen&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=7nP7JSAhIS&sig=EutjsehkGNfPYVkpJzzLTGvwapk&hl=en&ei=cPxNSp_eCYXk7AOu4KyKBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3 The Global Citizen Donella H. Meadows, 1991; 300 pp. Island Press]</ref> Her work is recognized as a formative influence on hundreds of other academic studies, government policy initiatives, and international agreements.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\u000a\u000aMeadows was a long-time member of the United States Association for the [[Club of Rome]], which instituted an award in her memory: "The US Association for the Club of Rome Donella Meadows Award in Sustainable Global Actions." This award is given to an outstanding individual who has created actions in a global framework toward the sustainability goals Meadows expressed in her writings.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\u000a\u000a== Work ==\u000a\u000a=== ''The Limits to Growth'' ===\u000a{{main article|The Limits to Growth}}\u000a\u000aIn 1972, she was on the MIT team that produced the global [[computer simulation|computer model]] "[[World3]]" for the [[Club of Rome]], providing the basis for ''The Limits to Growth.'' The book reported a study of long-term global trends in population, economics, and the environment. The book made headlines around the world and began a debate about the limits of [[Earth]]'s capacity to support human economic expansion\u2212a debate that continues to this day.<ref>"To Grow or not to Grow", Newsweek, March 13, 1972, pages 102-103</ref>\u000a\u000a===The Balaton Group===\u000aIn 1982, Donella Meadows and  [[Dennis Meadows]] created an international "network of networks" for leading researchers on resource use, environmental conservation, systems modeling, and sustainability. Since its foundation, the members have met at [[Lake Balaton]], in [[Hungary]], every autumn. While the formal name for the network was the International Network of Resource Information Centres (INRIC), it became more popularly known as the [[Balaton Group]] <ref>{{Cite web|title=Balaton Group History |url=http://www.balatongroup.org/FAQ.html |date=2010-02-05 |accessdate=2015-10-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205175146/http://www.balatongroup.org/FAQ.html |archivedate=February 5, 2010 }}</ref> based on the location of its meetings.\u000a\u000a=== Sustainability Institute and Related Organizations ===\u000aDonella Meadows was the founder of the Sustainability Institute, which combined research in global systems with practical demonstrations of [[sustainable development|sustainable]] living, including the development of a [[cohousing]] (or [[ecovillage]]) and organic farm at [[Cobb Hill]] in [[Hartland, Vermont]], in the United States.  In 2011, the Sustainability Institute, originally located adjacent to Cobb Hill, was renamed the Donella Meadows Institute and moved its offices to Norwich, Vermont. Additional organizations that sprang from the Sustainability Institute include [http://www.sustainablefood.org/ Sustainable Food Lab], [https://www.climateinteractive.org/ Climate Interactive] and [http://www.sustainabilityleadersnetwork.org/ Sustainability Leaders Network].\u000a\u000a=== State of the Village report ===\u000aIn 1990, Donella Meadows published the State of the Village report under the title, "Who lives in the 'Global Village'?"<ref>[http://www.empowermentresources.com/info2/theglobalvillage.html Meadows, Donnella. (1990, May 31). "Who lives in the 'Global Village'?" ''The Global Citizen'']</ref> which likened the world to a village of 1,000 people. Since then, "If the world were a village of 100 people"\u2212derived from her work but further reducing the numbers to those of a village of 100 people\u2212has been published by others in English, Spanish, and Japanese.\u000a\u000a=== Twelve leverage points ===\u000a{{Main article|Twelve leverage points}}\u000aMeadows published ''Leverage Points: Places to Intervene in a System'',  one of her best-known essays, in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sustainabilityinstitute.org/pubs/Leverage_Points.pdf |title=Leverage Points: Places to Intervene in a System |date=1999 |accessdate=2015-10-25 |website=The Sustainability Institute |publisher= |last=Meadows |first=Donella |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008160618/http://www.sustainabilityinstitute.org/pubs/Leverage_Points.pdf |archivedate=October 8, 2013 }}</ref>  It describes what types of interventions in a system (of any kind) are most effective, and which are least effective.\u000a\u000a== See also ==\u000a{{Portal|Systems science}}\u000a* [[Amory Lovins]]\u000a* [[Cobb Hill]]\u000a* [[Dennis Meadows]]\u000a* [[System dynamics]]\u000a* [[DYNAMO (programming language)]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist|30em}}\u000a\u000a== Further reading ==\u000a* Donella H. Meadows, Jorgen Randers and Dennis L. Meadows ''Limits to Growth-The 30 year Update'', 2004, hardcover ISBN 1-931498-51-2\u000a* Dennis L. Meadows, Donella H. Meadows, Eds. ''Toward Global Equilibrium: Collected Papers'', Pegasus Communications, 1973, hardcover ISBN 0-262-13143-9\u000a* Donella H. Meadows and J. M. Robinson, ''The Electronic Oracle: Computer Models and Social Decisions'', [http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/ John Wiley & Sons], 1985, hardcover, 462 pages, ISBN 0-471-90558-5\u000a* Donella H. Meadows, ''Global Citizen'', [http://www.islandpress.org/ Island Press], 1991, paperback 197 pages, ISBN 1-55963-058-2\u000a* Donella H. Meadows, et al.  ''Limits to Growth: A Report for the Club of Rome's Project on the Predicament of Mankind'', New American Library, 1977, paperback, ISBN 0-451-13695-0; Universe Books, paperback, 1972, 0\u201387663\u2013165\u20130 (scarce); ISBN Universe Books, hardcover, 1972, ISBN 0-87663-222-3 (scarce); [http://collections.dartmouth.edu/teitexts/meadows/diplomatic/meadows_ltg-diplomatic.html digital edition of 1972 printing], produced by the Dartmouth College Library.\u000a* Donella H. Meadows et al. ''Beyond the limits : global collapse or a sustainable future'', [http://www.earthscan.co.uk/ Earthscan Publications], 1992, ISBN 1-85383-130-1\u000a* Donella H. Meadows (2008) ''Thinking in Systems - A primer'' (Earthscan) ISBN 978-1-84407-726-7\u000a* Dennis L. Meadows, Donella H. Meadows and Jorgen Randers, ''Beyond the Limits: Confronting Global Collapse, Envisioning a Sustainable Future'', [http://www.chelseagreen.com/index.asp?bhcp=1 Chelsea Green Publishing], 1993, paperback, 320 pages, ISBN 0-930031-62-8\u000a* Donella H. Meadows, [[John M. Richardson (professor)|John M. Richardson]] and Gerhart Bruckmann, ''Groping in the Dark: The First Decade of Global Modelling'', [http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/ John Wiley & Sons], 1982, paperback, ISBN 0-471-10027-7\u000a* edited by Sandi Brockway, foreword by Marilyn Ferguson, introduction by Denis Hayes, preface by Donella H. Meadows, ''Macrocosm U. S. A.: Possibilities for a New Progressive Era...'', [http://www.macronet.org/ Macrocosm], 1993, paperback, 464 pages, ISBN 0-9632315-5-3\u000a* Michael J. Caduto, foreword by Donella H. Meadows, illustrated by Joan Thomson, ''Pond and Brook: A Guide to Nature in Freshwater Environments'', [http://www.dartmouth.edu/~upne/ University Press of New England], 1990, paperback, 288 pages, ISBN 0-87451-509-2\u000a* Ikeda Kayoko, C. Douglas Lummis, ''Si El Mundo Fuera Una Aldea De 100 Personas/if The World Were A Village Of 100 People'', Paperback, 64 pages, ISBN 84-7669-625-6. Japanese/English version: ISBN 4-8387-1361-4\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{Wikiquote}}\u000a*[http://www.donellameadows.org/ Donella Meadows Institute]\u000a*[http://ead.dartmouth.edu/html/ms1152_fullguide.html  Guide to the Papers of Donella H. Meadows, 1941-2007,  in the Dartmouth College Library]\u000a*[http://iisd1.iisd.ca/pcdf/meadows/ The Global Citizen, bi-weekly column by Meadows]\u000a*[http://www.pcdf.org/meadows/ Another link for Global Citizen]\u000a*[http://www.balatongroup.org/ The website of the Balaton Group (International Network of Resource Information Centers)]\u000a*[http://www.cobbhill.org/  Cobb Hill website]\u000a*[http://www.empowermentresources.com/info2/theglobalvillage.html A copy of her original Global Village report (based on 1000 people) ]\u000a*[http://www.miniature-earth.com/  The Miniature Earth project based on Donella Meadows text]\u000a----\u000a<!--The '''[[Dana Meadows]]''' are in the High Sierra of [[Yosemite National Park]].\u000aHas absolutely no relation to Donella "Dana" Meadows -->\u000a\u000a{{Systems}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT